{"id":"mai-b3di","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Subcommand discovery via plugin manifest","priority":1,"tags":["architecture","substrate"],"body":"## What\n\nAdd plugin manifest (`.maitake/plugins.toml`) and subcommand discovery to mai.\n\nWhen `mai foo` is not a built-in command, mai:\n1. Reads `.maitake/plugins.toml` (per-repo), falls back to `~/.maitake/plugins.toml` (global)\n2. Looks up `foo` in `[plugins]` section\n3. If found, execs the named binary with remaining args + MAI_REPO_PATH env\n4. If not found, prints \"unknown command 'foo'. Install mai-foo or add it to .maitake/plugins.toml\"\n\n### Manifest format\n\n```toml\n[plugins]\npr = \"mai-pr\"\ndocs = \"mai-docs\"\nchangelog = \"mai-changelog\"\n```\n\n### mai init writes default manifest\n\n`mai init` creates plugins.toml listing all bundled tools. Users add third-party tools manually.\n\n### Environment passed to plugins\n\n- `MAI_REPO_PATH` — absolute path to repo root\n- `MAI_MAITAKE_DIR` — absolute path to .maitake/\n- `MAI_JSON` — \"1\" if --json was passed\n- Remaining args passed through\n\n## Why\n\nExplicit, not magic. The manifest is the guardrail — you see exactly what's wired. No hidden PATH scanning.\n\n## Goal\nmai discovers and dispatches to external plugin binaries via explicit manifest\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] mai foo dispatches to mai-foo if listed in plugins.toml\n- [ ] mai foo shows helpful error if not in manifest and not built-in\n- [ ] mai init writes default plugins.toml with bundled tools\n- [ ] Per-repo manifest overrides global\n- [ ] MAI_REPO_PATH, MAI_MAITAKE_DIR, MAI_JSON env vars passed to plugins\n\n## Verification\n- [ ] Create a dummy mai-test binary, add to plugins.toml, mai test dispatches to it\n- [ ] Remove from manifest, mai test shows error\n- [ ] mai init creates plugins.toml\n- [ ] go test covers dispatch logic","timestamp":"2026-04-04T13:13:36Z","branch":"main"}

